	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_72138"><p><div class="quote"><p>If the Counter / LazyIterator example was written in Perl 5, one would use 'sub { $count++ }', isn't it? Why the same method, i.e. 'sub { }' as circumfix operator for block in Perl 6?</p></div><p>Yeah, <code>sub { }</code> would be the nearest equivalent in Perl 5. It creates a reference to a closure. You can write that in Perl 6 as well, but the <code>sub</code> keyword gives the closure a bit more of a "shell", as outlined in <a href="http://use.perl.org/~masak/journal/38123" title="perl.org" rel="nofollow">this post</a> [perl.org].</p><p><div class="quote"><p>P.S. Would you resubmit this blog post to <a href="http://perlgeek.de/blog-en" title="perlgeek.de" rel="nofollow">http://perlgeek.de/blog-en</a> [perlgeek.de] for it to be easier to find?</p></div><p>If you want to read Moritz's and my blog posts in the same feed, I suggest you check out <a href="http://planetsix.perl.org/" title="perl.org" rel="nofollow">Planet Perl 6</a> [perl.org].</p></div>
		
	
